<doc id="197902" wikidata="Q4097090" url="?curid=197902" title="Broad (English gold coin)">
<text>The Broad was an English coin worth 20 shillings (20/-) issued by the Commonwealth of England in 1656. It was a milled gold coin weighing 9.0–9.1 grams, with a diameter of 29 or 30 millimetres, designed by Thomas Simon (also called Symonds).

The obverse of the coin depicts the Lord Protector Oliver Cromwell as a laureated Roman emperor, with the Latin inscription [Olivarius Dei Gratia Res Publicae Angliae, Scotiae et Hiberniae etc. Protector] — &quot;Oliver, by the Grace of God, of the Republic of England, Scotland, Ireland etc., Protector&quot;, while the reverse shows a crowned shield depicting the arms of the Commonwealth with the inscription -- &quot;Peace is sought through war&quot;.

The current value of the coin in &quot;very fine&quot; to &quot;extremely fine&quot; condition is £27,000 to £54,000.

A piedfort version of the coin with an edge inscription is known as a Fifty shilling piece. This is extremely rare, and there are very few examples as it is probably a pattern.

